'''Kokuga-ryō''' (国衙領) is a term in [[historical studies]] referring to the [[public domains]] ({{ill|Kōryō|ja|公領|12=draft}}) from the mid-[[Heian period]]. The term "kokuga" refers to the government offices of the {{ill|Provinces of Japan|ja|令制国|12=draft}}.

This concept is contrasted with {{ill|Shōen|ja|荘園|12=draft}} (private domains). Together, they form the basis of the {{ill|Shōen-Kōryō system|ja|荘園公領制|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
By the [[10th century]], the tax system based on {{ill|Ancient Japanese census system|ja|古代の戸籍制度|12=draft}} and {{ill|Handen shūju|ja|班田収授|12=draft}} under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft}} had largely collapsed. The {{ill|Imperial Court in Kyoto|ja|朝廷|12=draft}} began delegating tax collection responsibilities to the local {{ill|Kokushi|ja|国司|12=draft}} (provincial governors), particularly the chief governors known as {{ill|Zuryō|ja|受領|12=draft}}. The zuryō, in turn, entrusted the practical tasks to a class of local officials known as {{ill|Zaichō kanjin|ja|在庁官人|12=draft}}, often from the landowning class referred to as the "wealthy class" (富豪の輩), under a system called {{ill|Kokushi contract system|ja|国司請負制|12=draft}}.

The zuryō's primary role was to ensure the collection and remittance of taxes from public domains to the court and high-Ranking nobles, such as the {{ill|Sesshō and Kampaku|ja|摂関家|12=draft}} and major temples, during their tenure. When tax collection was delayed, the right to collect the equivalent taxes was often transferred to these entities, creating patches of tax-exempt land known as {{ill|Kokumen-shō|ja|国免荘|12=draft}}, which gradually expanded. These newly established shōen increasingly pressured the collection of taxes from public domains.

In the {{ill|11th century|ja|11世紀|12=draft}}, frequent fires at the {{ill|Imperial Palace|ja|内裏|12=draft}} and major temples necessitated extraordinary taxation ({{ill|Kokuan|ja|国宛|12=draft}}) on public domains to fund reconstruction. However, tax collection became increasingly challenging, and shōen that were previously unofficially exempted from taxation were included under {{ill|Ichikoku Heimin-yaku|ja|一国平均役|12=draft}} (an equal distribution of tax burdens across all domains within a province). To formalize this system, the court issued {{ill|Shōen Consolidation Orders|ja|荘園整理令|12=draft}}, which stopped the creation of new shōen from a certain year but also officially recognized existing kokumen-shō, subjecting them to temporary taxation.

These orders also simplified taxation by consolidating scattered shōen into single entities, allowing the aristocracy or major temples to send {{ill|Shōkan|ja|荘官|12=draft}} (estate managers) to administer and collect taxes as delegated by the state. Thus, shōen evolved into governed territories with a unified administrative structure.

As a result, provincial administration shifted from unified control under the zuryō to a dual system of land and population governance, divided between shōen managed by shōkan and public domains controlled by zuryō. {{ill|Yoshihiko Amino|ja|網野善彦|12=draft}}, a prominent historian, introduced the concept of the {{ill|Shōen-Kōryō system|ja|荘園公領制|12=draft}} to describe medieval Japanese society composed of these two land systems.

With the establishment of the {{ill|Kamakura shogunate|ja|鎌倉幕府|12=draft}}, public domains gradually fell under the influence of {{ill|Shugo|ja|守護|12=draft}} (provincial constables) and {{ill|Jitō|ja|地頭|12=draft}} (manorial stewards). During the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代|12=draft}}, public domains were designated as {{ill|Military provisioning areas|ja|兵粮料所|12=draft}} but were often absorbed into shugo territories. Even though the {{ill|Meitoku Agreement|ja|明徳の和約|12=draft}} designated public domains as the property of the {{ill|Daikakuji line|ja|大覚寺統|12=draft}}, only minimal taxes were actually collected, leaving the Daikakuji line in financial distress. Despite this, public domains persisted until they were ultimately abolished during the {{ill|Taikō land surveys|ja|太閤検地|12=draft}}.

