'''Kokuga-ryō''' (国衙領) is a term in [[historical studies]] referring to the [[public domains]] ({{ill|Kōryō|ja|公領|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōryō|qq=}}) from the mid-[[Heian period]]. The term "kokuga" refers to the government offices of the [[:en:Provinces of Japan|Provinces of Japan]].
This concept is contrasted with [[:en:Manorialism|Shōen]] (private domains). Together, they form the basis of the {{ill|Shōen-Kōryō system|ja|荘園公領制|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōen-Kōryō system|qq=}}.
== Overview == By the [[10th century]], the tax system based on {{ill|Ancient Japanese census system|ja|古代の戸籍制度|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ancient Japanese census system|qq=}} and {{ill|Handen shūju|ja|班田収授|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Handen shūju|qq=}} under the [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]] had largely collapsed. The [[:en:Royal court|Imperial Court in Kyoto]] began delegating tax collection responsibilities to the local [[:en:Kokushi (official)|Kokushi]] (provincial governors), particularly the chief governors known as {{ill|Zuryō|ja|受領|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zuryō|qq=}}. The zuryō, in turn, entrusted the practical tasks to a class of local officials known as {{ill|Zaichō kanjin|ja|在庁官人|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zaichō kanjin|qq=}}, often from the landowning class referred to as the "wealthy class" (富豪の輩), under a system called {{ill|Kokushi contract system|ja|国司請負制|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi contract system|qq=}}.
The zuryō's primary role was to ensure the collection and remittance of taxes from public domains to the court and high-Ranking nobles, such as the {{ill|Sesshō and Kampaku|ja|摂関家|1=Five regent houses|2=ja|3=摂家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sesshō and Kampaku|qq=}} and major temples, during their tenure. When tax collection was delayed, the right to collect the equivalent taxes was often transferred to these entities, creating patches of tax-exempt land known as {{ill|Kokumen-shō|ja|国免荘|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokumen-shō|qq=}}, which gradually expanded. These newly established shōen increasingly pressured the collection of taxes from public domains.
In the [[:en:11th century|11th century]], frequent fires at the {{ill|Imperial Palace|ja|内裏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Palace|qq=}} and major temples necessitated extraordinary taxation ({{ill|Kokuan|ja|国宛|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokuan|qq=}}) on public domains to fund reconstruction. However, tax collection became increasingly challenging, and shōen that were previously unofficially exempted from taxation were included under {{ill|Ichikoku Heimin-yaku|ja|一国平均役|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichikoku Heimin-yaku|qq=}} (an equal distribution of tax burdens across all domains within a province). To formalize this system, the court issued {{ill|Shōen Consolidation Orders|ja|荘園整理令|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōen Consolidation Orders|qq=}}, which stopped the creation of new shōen from a certain year but also officially recognized existing kokumen-shō, subjecting them to temporary taxation.
These orders also simplified taxation by consolidating scattered shōen into single entities, allowing the aristocracy or major temples to send {{ill|Shōkan|ja|荘官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkan|qq=}} (estate managers) to administer and collect taxes as delegated by the state. Thus, shōen evolved into governed territories with a unified administrative structure.
As a result, provincial administration shifted from unified control under the zuryō to a dual system of land and population governance, divided between shōen managed by shōkan and public domains controlled by zuryō. [[:en:Yoshihiko Amino|Yoshihiko Amino]], a prominent historian, introduced the concept of the {{ill|Shōen-Kōryō system|ja|荘園公領制|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōen-Kōryō system|qq=}} to describe medieval Japanese society composed of these two land systems.
With the establishment of the [[:en:Kamakura shogunate|Kamakura shogunate]], public domains gradually fell under the influence of [[:en:Shugo|Shugo]] (provincial constables) and [[:en:Jitō|Jitō]] (manorial stewards). During the [[:en:Northern and Southern Courts period (disambiguation)|Nanboku-chō period]], public domains were designated as {{ill|Military provisioning areas|ja|兵粮料所|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Military provisioning areas|qq=}} but were often absorbed into shugo territories. Even though the {{ill|Meitoku Agreement|ja|明徳の和約|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meitoku Agreement|qq=}} designated public domains as the property of the {{ill|Daikakuji line|ja|大覚寺統|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daikakuji line|qq=}}, only minimal taxes were actually collected, leaving the Daikakuji line in financial distress. Despite this, public domains persisted until they were ultimately abolished during the {{ill|Taikō land surveys|ja|太閤検地|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taikō land surveys|qq=}}.
