In the [[:en:11th century|11th century]], frequent fires at the {{ill|Imperial Palace|ja|内裏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Palace|qq=|1=Dairi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q3012148}} and major temples necessitated extraordinary taxation ({{ill|Kokuan|ja|国宛|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokuan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 国充|1=Kokuan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11420477}}) on public domains to fund reconstruction. However, tax collection became increasingly challenging, and shōen that were previously unofficially exempted from taxation were included under {{ill|Ichikoku Heimin-yaku|ja|一国平均役|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichikoku Heimin-yaku|qq=|1=Ichikoku Heimin-yaku|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11352489}} (an equal distribution of tax burdens across all domains within a province). To formalize this system, the court issued {{ill|Shōen Consolidation Orders|ja|荘園整理令|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōen Consolidation Orders|qq=|1=Shōen Consolidation Orders|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11618907}}, which stopped the creation of new shōen from a certain year but also officially recognized existing kokumen-shō, subjecting them to temporary taxation.

These orders also simplified taxation by consolidating scattered shōen into single entities, allowing the aristocracy or major temples to send {{ill|Shōkan|ja|荘官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkan|qq=|1=shōkan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11618914}} (estate managers) to administer and collect taxes as delegated by the state. Thus, shōen evolved into governed territories with a unified administrative structure.

As a result, provincial administration shifted from unified control under the zuryō to a dual system of land and population governance, divided between shōen managed by shōkan and public domains controlled by zuryō. [[:en:Yoshihiko Amino|Yoshihiko Amino]], a prominent historian, introduced the concept of the {{ill|Shōen-Kōryō system|ja|荘園公領制|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōen-Kōryō system|qq=|1=shōen-kokugaryō system|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11618906}} to describe medieval Japanese society composed of these two land systems.

With the establishment of the [[:en:Kamakura shogunate|Kamakura shogunate]], public domains gradually fell under the influence of [[:en:Shugo|Shugo]] (provincial constables) and [[:en:Jitō|Jitō]] (manorial stewards). During the [[:en:Northern and Southern Courts period (disambiguation)|Nanboku-chō period]], public domains were designated as {{ill|Military provisioning areas|ja|兵粮料所|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Military provisioning areas|qq=|1=Military provisioning areas|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11393687}} but were often absorbed into shugo territories. Even though the {{ill|Meitoku Agreement|ja|明徳の和約|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meitoku Agreement|qq=|1=Meitoku Peace Accord|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11087845}} designated public domains as the property of the {{ill|Daikakuji line|ja|大覚寺統|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daikakuji line|qq=|1=Daikakuji line|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q10937983}}, only minimal taxes were actually collected, leaving the Daikakuji line in financial distress. Despite this, public domains persisted until they were ultimately abolished during the {{ill|Taikō land surveys|ja|太閤検地|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taikō land surveys|qq=|1=Taikō kenchi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q8193888}}.

